1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:11,010 --> 00:00:12,760
Uncle, it's spring.

3
00:00:14,050 --> 00:00:14,950
So what?

4
00:00:15,750 --> 00:00:17,450
In spring I always wash your bedsheet.

5
00:00:18,050 --> 00:00:21,750
Hey, Ivuska, it's barely been a month since it stopped being soft and smelling like flowers.

6
00:00:22,050 --> 00:00:24,170
So you hid it from me in the closet again.

7
00:00:24,170 --> 00:00:25,170
They're beautiful.

8
00:00:25,850 --> 00:00:29,560
I bought them from that old geezer who normally hands out the Watchtower in front of the supermarket.

9
00:00:29,560 --> 00:00:30,560
Yeah, spring.

10
00:00:30,700 --> 00:00:30,960
Yeah.

11
00:00:33,550 --> 00:00:35,150
What are these flowers called?

12
00:00:35,220 --> 00:00:35,700
Roses.

13
00:00:36,720 --> 00:00:37,240
Roses.

14
00:00:37,240 --> 00:00:41,060
Marcelka, don't let him near the flowers.

15
00:00:41,450 --> 00:00:44,550
Either he's trying to roll something from them, or he eats them.

16
00:00:44,950 --> 00:00:48,460
Last time he polished off four planters of tulips.

17
00:00:48,650 --> 00:00:52,850
He made onion soup from them.

18
00:00:55,050 --> 00:00:56,050
Uncle.

19
00:00:57,450 --> 00:00:59,550
Is something wrong with you?

20
00:01:00,150 --> 00:01:00,900
No, why?

21
00:01:00,900 --> 00:01:03,700
I also noticed something's going on with you.

22
00:01:03,780 --> 00:01:05,420
This morning you greeted me.

23
00:01:05,600 --> 00:01:06,220
Hey, bimbo.

24
00:01:06,440 --> 00:01:06,920
Oh, no.

25
00:01:07,550 --> 00:01:09,750
Good morning, Marcelka.

26
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:11,100
I didn't say it like that.

27
00:01:11,100 --> 00:01:11,880
Yes you did.

28
00:01:11,880 --> 00:01:14,320
And he held the door for two old ladies on their way out.

29
00:01:14,550 --> 00:01:16,860
He yelled after them, at least get lost, you idiots.

30
00:01:16,860 --> 00:01:17,800
Exactly, he didn't.

31
00:01:18,250 --> 00:01:19,450
Unusual.

32
00:01:21,850 --> 00:01:23,050
Uncle, what have you got there?

33
00:01:23,980 --> 00:01:24,540
Nothing.

34
00:01:25,220 --> 00:01:25,740
Show me your hand.

35
00:01:26,940 --> 00:01:27,500
The other one.

36
00:01:33,070 --> 00:01:33,630
Shakira?

37
00:01:35,880 --> 00:01:36,440
Beyonce?

38
00:01:38,450 --> 00:01:41,130
Lucka Vondrackova?

39
00:01:41,130 --> 00:01:43,450
You normally wouldn't touch her with a ten-foot pole.

40
00:01:43,630 --> 00:01:44,990
I was just looking at the covers.

41
00:01:45,130 --> 00:01:45,690
Exactly.

42
00:01:46,290 --> 00:01:47,270
I need to see Dad.

43
00:01:47,390 --> 00:01:47,810
Why?

44
00:01:48,350 --> 00:01:50,380
I just looked at it and sniffed it here, what's the big deal?

45
00:01:50,550 --> 00:01:51,750
You know damn well why.

46
00:01:52,350 --> 00:01:53,250
Marcelka, keep an eye on him.

47
00:01:55,950 --> 00:01:59,450
And if he does anything suspicious, write it all down immediately.

48
00:02:34,470 --> 00:02:35,310
Exclamation mark.

49
00:02:37,750 --> 00:02:39,850
Colon, dash, parenthesis.

50
00:02:40,250 --> 00:02:41,430
Damn, here we go again.

51
00:02:45,080 --> 00:02:45,780
Hi, Iva.

52
00:02:45,940 --> 00:02:46,260
Hi.

53
00:02:46,520 --> 00:02:48,540
Do you know what this means?

54
00:02:49,020 --> 00:02:50,580
Colon, dash, parenthesis.

55
00:02:51,050 --> 00:02:54,650
I looked it up in a Slovak-Czech dictionary, but I don't know where a colon is in the alphabet.

56
00:02:55,450 --> 00:02:57,650
You've been chatting with that fake Slovak girl.

57
00:02:57,850 --> 00:02:59,450
Dana happens to be sincere.

58
00:03:00,350 --> 00:03:04,170
She just wrote me that I understand her like no one else in the world and that she wants to meet me in person.

59
00:03:04,550 --> 00:03:06,350
Oh, I'm sure.

60
00:03:07,050 --> 00:03:10,950
Lexa, you understand me like no one else in the world, I'd like to meet you in person.

61
00:03:11,050 --> 00:03:14,450
If I were you, I wouldn't risk it.

62
00:03:15,050 --> 00:03:17,850
Unless you want a date with a fifty-year-old bald guy.

63
00:03:18,550 --> 00:03:21,250
I don't think she'd take Dad on a date.

64
00:03:21,340 --> 00:03:22,560
Lexa, you're such a loser.

65
00:03:22,560 --> 00:03:25,720
It's been proven that every pretty girl on the internet is a guy.

66
00:03:25,950 --> 00:03:26,780
That's not true.

67
00:03:27,050 --> 00:03:28,350
She sent me her photo.

68
00:03:30,250 --> 00:03:31,450
Wow, really pretty.

69
00:03:32,150 --> 00:03:33,590
Plus she reminds me of someone.

70
00:03:35,250 --> 00:03:35,950
Like Venus, but prettier.

71
00:03:39,650 --> 00:03:41,850
A bald guy reads the same magazines as me.

72
00:03:41,940 --> 00:03:44,520
He sent you a photo of a model from an ad for a hair remover.

73
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:46,620
She did say she's a model, actually.

74
00:03:46,920 --> 00:03:47,440
Right.

75
00:03:48,150 --> 00:03:50,350
And she studies archaeology and Hebrew.

76
00:03:50,950 --> 00:03:53,250
The world is just teeming with those.

77
00:03:53,250 --> 00:03:56,350
And she's definitely going to Africa to save children with malaria.

78
00:03:56,400 --> 00:03:57,580
I talked her out of that.

79
00:03:58,850 --> 00:04:01,540
Lexa, Dad will be here any minute, I need to discuss something with him.

80
00:04:01,850 --> 00:04:02,580
I don't mind.

81
00:04:02,850 --> 00:04:04,050
And neither does Dana.

82
00:04:04,140 --> 00:04:05,040
Scram, Lexa.

83
00:04:05,340 --> 00:04:07,740
See you tomorrow then, little beak.

84
00:04:07,940 --> 00:04:09,000
Off you go, little beak.

85
00:04:09,860 --> 00:04:10,740
The bald guy will wait.

86
00:04:12,250 --> 00:04:14,220
Once I have a laptop, nothing will stand between me and Dana.

87
00:04:14,450 --> 00:04:17,350
And she'll finally press you to her hairy chest.

88
00:04:17,510 --> 00:04:18,030
Scram.

89
00:04:30,140 --> 00:04:30,660
Dad.

90
00:04:32,350 --> 00:04:34,050
Ozzak sniffed the flowers today.

91
00:04:35,350 --> 00:04:36,550
What, is he dead?

92
00:04:36,950 --> 00:04:41,400
No, then I'd say something like, Dad, all the beers in the fridge are yours now.

93
00:04:41,400 --> 00:04:42,920
But he's okay, right?

94
00:04:44,550 --> 00:04:47,850
Today he sold a Madonna compilation just because a woman asked for it.

95
00:04:48,750 --> 00:04:50,050
Well, that could've been a coincidence.

96
00:04:50,750 --> 00:04:52,150
He put on cologne this morning.

97
00:04:52,550 --> 00:04:54,710
Maybe he just missed his mouth.

98
00:04:54,950 --> 00:04:56,950
He told Marcelka she looks nice.

99
00:04:57,450 --> 00:04:58,050
Really?

100
00:04:59,050 --> 00:05:02,050
You know, I was thinking, could it be that thing?

101
00:05:02,950 --> 00:05:06,360
No, it can't be that, a tick bit him or something.

102
00:05:07,650 --> 00:05:09,350
Admit it, spring fever is hitting Ozzak again.

103
00:05:09,550 --> 00:05:12,300
Jesus, Mary, he just promised he'd never do it again.

104
00:05:12,300 --> 00:05:13,340
You can't fight nature.

105
00:05:14,040 --> 00:05:15,920
Maybe this year it'll turn out normal.

106
00:05:16,220 --> 00:05:22,740
And that is normal — a guy wants to have fun, a woman thinks it's love, the guy goes back to beer and the woman wants revenge.

107
00:05:23,040 --> 00:05:24,480
You know, does that seem normal to you?

108
00:05:24,620 --> 00:05:25,020
Of course.

109
00:05:26,080 --> 00:05:30,480
What's not normal is that Ozzak always picks some woman who can destroy us.

110
00:05:31,040 --> 00:05:34,300
Yeah, like when he picked up your tax auditor?

111
00:05:34,460 --> 00:05:36,240
Yeah, we almost ended up under a bridge.

112
00:05:36,480 --> 00:05:38,140
Yeah, but then she got married and there was peace.

113
00:05:38,750 --> 00:05:42,050
Except the policewoman from anti-piracy didn't get married.

114
00:05:42,350 --> 00:05:45,850
If they hadn't transferred her to homicide, she'd still be checking every CD in the store.

115
00:05:46,650 --> 00:05:48,950
Wait, was that the woman who dug up our garden?

116
00:05:49,150 --> 00:05:52,350
No, the garden was dug up by Jana from the drug squad.

117
00:05:53,050 --> 00:05:55,250
Why are these women so vengeful?

118
00:05:55,750 --> 00:05:56,650
What are we going to do?

119
00:05:58,050 --> 00:05:59,050
What about grandma's?

120
00:05:59,450 --> 00:06:01,650
Like that time when he dumped the pyrotechnician.

121
00:06:02,950 --> 00:06:05,750
And we're not going to leave him alone with Marcelka.

122
00:06:06,340 --> 00:06:07,420
Jesus Christ.

123
00:06:07,920 --> 00:06:08,640
Marcelka.

124
00:06:09,150 --> 00:06:10,480
She hates him too.

125
00:06:10,750 --> 00:06:12,250
You can't fight nature.

126
00:06:14,320 --> 00:06:15,360
Come in.

127
00:06:16,220 --> 00:06:17,760
Ozzak.

128
00:06:18,400 --> 00:06:20,380
And then I started working at a garden center.

129
00:06:20,860 --> 00:06:22,080
That was my first job.

130
00:06:22,520 --> 00:06:26,220
But then the cops came, collected all the plants and burned them.

131
00:06:26,360 --> 00:06:27,560
And that was the end of that job.

132
00:06:27,620 --> 00:06:28,140
Oops.

133
00:06:30,160 --> 00:06:32,820
Ozzak, what's the meaning of this?

134
00:06:33,120 --> 00:06:35,600
Mr. Ozzak is telling me about his life.

135
00:06:35,740 --> 00:06:37,560
Did you know he was a porn surgeon?

136
00:06:37,740 --> 00:06:37,940
Well.

137
00:06:39,120 --> 00:06:40,260
Here you go.

138
00:06:41,240 --> 00:06:42,380
Would you like anything else?

139
00:06:43,450 --> 00:06:45,340
No thank you, I have everything.

140
00:06:45,340 --> 00:06:46,040
That's enough!

141
00:06:47,450 --> 00:06:51,150
Iva, take Marcelka to the kitchen immediately, you, bro, go to your room.

142
00:06:51,760 --> 00:06:52,240
But...

143
00:06:52,240 --> 00:06:53,560
Come on, it's for your own good.

144
00:06:53,640 --> 00:06:54,000
Come on.

145
00:06:54,560 --> 00:06:55,620
What are you doing?

146
00:06:55,620 --> 00:06:56,240
I saw her first.

147
00:06:56,600 --> 00:06:57,080
Right now.

148
00:06:57,080 --> 00:06:58,780
We were just chatting.

149
00:06:58,780 --> 00:07:00,360
I'll have a chat with you about that.

150
00:07:00,440 --> 00:07:00,740
But.

151
00:07:05,850 --> 00:07:06,920
You have to excuse him.

152
00:07:07,050 --> 00:07:07,550
But for God's sake, why?

153
00:07:08,840 --> 00:07:11,000
Today he acted like a human being for the first time.

154
00:07:11,580 --> 00:07:13,780
Marcelka, I won't beat around the bush.

155
00:07:14,450 --> 00:07:15,650
Take a vacation.

156
00:07:16,910 --> 00:07:18,010
Did I do something wrong?

157
00:07:18,450 --> 00:07:20,250
You want to fire me?

158
00:07:20,270 --> 00:07:21,390
How could you think that?

159
00:07:22,450 --> 00:07:26,730
My husband sends people on vacation like this and when they come back, they don't have jobs anymore.

160
00:07:26,730 --> 00:07:27,890
Those who come back.

161
00:07:28,410 --> 00:07:29,730
No, I'm serious.

162
00:07:29,850 --> 00:07:32,310
Go, Marcelka, come back in a month.

163
00:07:32,490 --> 00:07:34,730
Wait, it's never lasted longer than three weeks.

164
00:07:34,890 --> 00:07:37,070
Fine, three weeks then, everything will be fine after that.

165
00:07:38,250 --> 00:07:41,050
For God's sake, Tomas, what's going on?

166
00:07:42,430 --> 00:07:42,830
Nothing.

167
00:07:43,650 --> 00:07:44,550
Nothing's going on.

168
00:07:45,130 --> 00:07:45,530
Wow.

169
00:07:56,850 --> 00:07:59,350
Last time we agreed you'd report it.

170
00:07:59,750 --> 00:08:01,650
It's not that big a deal, is it?

171
00:08:01,730 --> 00:08:03,890
Not a big deal — you hit on your coworker.

172
00:08:04,210 --> 00:08:08,570
Ozzak, we're your family and when spring hits you, you have to tell us.

173
00:08:08,750 --> 00:08:10,330
Should I also report when I go for a beer?

174
00:08:10,610 --> 00:08:13,890
When you go for a beer, bro, everything around you doesn't collapse.

175
00:08:14,150 --> 00:08:14,890
Yeah it does.

176
00:08:15,050 --> 00:08:16,610
Yeah, mainly and God knows what else.

177
00:08:16,930 --> 00:08:19,310
Be glad we caught it early.

178
00:08:19,370 --> 00:08:21,290
You want Marcelka to dig up our garden?

179
00:08:21,850 --> 00:08:24,950
Yeah, Janicka, that one really should've grabbed a pitchfork.

180
00:08:24,950 --> 00:08:27,670
Ozzak, you simply have a ban and that's that.

181
00:08:27,850 --> 00:08:28,910
You have no right to do that.

182
00:08:29,750 --> 00:08:31,350
I'm ordering you as your...

183
00:08:32,200 --> 00:08:33,180
Younger brother.

184
00:08:33,180 --> 00:08:38,020
I'd like to know who decided that an older brother always has to listen to his younger one.

185
00:08:38,020 --> 00:08:38,820
It's in the constitution.

186
00:08:40,450 --> 00:08:41,830
Can I at least go to the hallway?

187
00:08:41,910 --> 00:08:42,970
Absolutely not!

188
00:08:43,350 --> 00:08:46,610
The building manager just stopped sending you hate messages a month ago.

189
00:08:46,690 --> 00:08:49,210
I'm not going to risk her taking our basement again.

190
00:08:49,910 --> 00:08:52,410
Ruzenka, hmm, she's got some...

191
00:08:52,410 --> 00:08:53,090
Ozzak!

192
00:08:54,550 --> 00:08:55,230
Hello.

193
00:08:55,550 --> 00:08:58,530
Wow, Mr. Ozzak, I ran into the building manager and she's got some...

194
00:08:58,530 --> 00:08:58,850
Lexa!

195
00:08:59,550 --> 00:09:00,350
Buzz off.

196
00:09:00,430 --> 00:09:00,870
Lexa!

197
00:09:00,870 --> 00:09:03,950
Stop me all you want, love conquers all.

198
00:09:04,250 --> 00:09:08,710
My thoughts exactly, Mom was supposed to get me a laptop and then nothing will stand between me and Diana.

199
00:09:08,710 --> 00:09:09,490
Who's Diana?

200
00:09:09,490 --> 00:09:12,570
She's a guy who likes young boys.

201
00:09:12,750 --> 00:09:16,050
Uncle Horvat went to the store for the laptop three times already, but they were always open.

202
00:09:16,050 --> 00:09:17,050
You mean closed, right?

203
00:09:17,750 --> 00:09:18,950
Mom said open.

204
00:09:19,340 --> 00:09:20,580
That does sound weird though.

205
00:09:22,450 --> 00:09:23,050
Lexa, tell your sister she can't visit Iva.

206
00:09:23,250 --> 00:09:28,250
Until further notice, no women are allowed in this apartment.

207
00:09:28,550 --> 00:09:29,650
And Dana can come?

208
00:09:29,950 --> 00:09:30,920
Dana can come.

209
00:09:30,920 --> 00:09:31,780
Women can't.

210
00:09:38,550 --> 00:09:40,250
Why are they sending me on vacation?

211
00:09:40,350 --> 00:09:41,590
Did I do something wrong?

212
00:09:42,150 --> 00:09:45,090
I've got the invoices in order, I got rid of the mold on the wall.

213
00:09:45,270 --> 00:09:46,130
You used lye?

214
00:09:46,430 --> 00:09:48,170
Yes, Ozzak licked it right off himself.

215
00:09:48,370 --> 00:09:51,990
He probably ate another expired hamburger patty and needed to fix the taste.

216
00:09:53,050 --> 00:09:54,430
It was actually nice of him.

217
00:09:54,430 --> 00:09:56,390
And he's been so pleasant lately.

218
00:09:56,570 --> 00:09:57,810
Are you confusing him with someone?

219
00:09:57,810 --> 00:09:59,070
Like someone pleasant?

220
00:09:59,670 --> 00:10:01,090
He's like a different person.

221
00:10:01,410 --> 00:10:02,430
He opened the door for me.

222
00:10:02,710 --> 00:10:03,090
Beer.

223
00:10:03,190 --> 00:10:04,250
He complimented my hairdo.

224
00:10:04,750 --> 00:10:05,550
Oh damn.

225
00:10:06,250 --> 00:10:07,350
Here we go again.

226
00:10:07,750 --> 00:10:10,820
Maybe I should send Sasa to grandma's this year.

227
00:10:10,820 --> 00:10:11,920
If I were you.

228
00:10:12,550 --> 00:10:14,460
I'd rather go somewhere far away.

229
00:10:14,650 --> 00:10:17,340
I can't leave Mr. Ozzak alone.

230
00:10:17,340 --> 00:10:17,620
You see?

231
00:10:17,950 --> 00:10:19,120
You feel it too, don't you?

232
00:10:19,120 --> 00:10:19,680
What?

233
00:10:20,150 --> 00:10:21,080
Ozzak, of course.

234
00:10:21,350 --> 00:10:25,140
Well, it's true that lately he smells like freshly washed windows.

235
00:10:25,140 --> 00:10:26,120
But it's nice.

236
00:10:27,950 --> 00:10:29,160
Ladies, I'll put it simply.

237
00:10:29,350 --> 00:10:31,450
Once in a while it comes over Ozzak...

238
00:10:31,850 --> 00:10:33,840
And no woman is safe around him.

239
00:10:33,840 --> 00:10:34,960
Around Ozzak?

240
00:10:35,750 --> 00:10:36,950
Pheromones, I'd say.

241
00:10:37,250 --> 00:10:38,550
Or something from outer space.

242
00:10:39,150 --> 00:10:47,250
Either way, first he starts being likable, then tells stories from his life, offers you a beer, and if you're not careful, the worst happens.

243
00:10:48,490 --> 00:10:49,910
That's nonsense.

244
00:10:49,910 --> 00:10:51,570
When I want to be, I'm like a bank.

245
00:10:52,310 --> 00:10:52,870
Tunneled?

246
00:10:53,050 --> 00:10:53,610
Impregnable.

247
00:10:53,610 --> 00:10:55,770
Yeah, that's what the one who lasted three days said too.

248
00:10:56,050 --> 00:10:56,910
Well excuse me.

249
00:10:57,250 --> 00:10:59,550
He has his bright moments, but he's a brute.

250
00:10:59,650 --> 00:11:02,850
And only some idiot could fall for him.

251
00:11:02,950 --> 00:11:04,010
Don't be so sure.

252
00:11:04,350 --> 00:11:07,790
When he turns it on, the best you can do is lock yourself in the fridge.

253
00:11:08,050 --> 00:11:11,150
Hmm, I'd like to see that.

254
00:11:17,370 --> 00:11:19,550
Wow, Mr. Ozzak, you're a real stud.

255
00:11:19,550 --> 00:11:22,830
They have to lock you at home so women don't throw themselves at you.

256
00:11:23,250 --> 00:11:24,110
It's the opposite for me.

257
00:11:24,450 --> 00:11:26,250
Women lock me out.

258
00:11:27,030 --> 00:11:27,550
Women.

259
00:11:28,950 --> 00:11:31,550
You bang on the door in vain, fake an epileptic seizure.

260
00:11:32,150 --> 00:11:33,750
Good thing I've got this.

261
00:11:35,150 --> 00:11:36,450
These boxes are women.

262
00:11:37,950 --> 00:11:39,350
There's basically nothing else in there.

263
00:11:39,700 --> 00:11:40,180
What kind?

264
00:11:40,850 --> 00:11:41,550
Well, all kinds.

265
00:11:41,740 --> 00:11:43,500
Just type www.

266
00:11:42,720 --> 00:11:43,700
iwantawoman.

267
00:11:43,500 --> 00:11:45,260
cz and then these categories open up.

268
00:11:45,950 --> 00:11:47,350
Poetry, lust, plastic windows.

269
00:11:49,650 --> 00:11:50,550
That's just an ad.

270
00:11:50,640 --> 00:11:52,320
But there are tons of categories, see?

271
00:11:52,320 --> 00:11:55,150
Girl seeking girl, casual flirt, serious only.

272
00:11:57,150 --> 00:11:58,350
What does "I'll come right away" mean?

273
00:11:58,760 --> 00:11:59,980
Like for lunch?

274
00:12:01,450 --> 00:12:02,450
No, it just means I'll come right away.

275
00:12:02,950 --> 00:12:04,550
Not for us, we want a long-term relationship.

276
00:12:05,970 --> 00:12:06,450
I see.

277
00:12:07,150 --> 00:12:08,150
But me and Deana.

278
00:12:08,350 --> 00:12:09,300
That's something completely different.

279
00:12:09,300 --> 00:12:09,500
Yeah.

280
00:12:09,950 --> 00:12:12,760
So I'm supposed to pick a woman like a CD in a store?

281
00:12:12,760 --> 00:12:13,380
Exactly.

282
00:12:14,050 --> 00:12:16,850
Just register and then you just click on her.

283
00:12:18,350 --> 00:12:19,550
What do I do to her?

284
00:12:19,950 --> 00:12:20,750
Well, click.

285
00:12:21,250 --> 00:12:22,150
You know that, right?

286
00:12:22,700 --> 00:12:23,120
Sure.

287
00:12:23,950 --> 00:12:24,680
I'm not stupid.

288
00:12:26,350 --> 00:12:27,750
And then you just wait for a reply.

289
00:12:27,860 --> 00:12:28,460
This internet thing.

290
00:12:29,450 --> 00:12:31,450
One click and I met Diana.

291
00:12:31,840 --> 00:12:32,260
I see.

292
00:12:33,150 --> 00:12:38,450
Hey, Lexa, let me use that computer for a bit.

293
00:12:40,550 --> 00:12:43,050
I need to calculate something.

294
00:12:46,950 --> 00:12:50,300
Calculate something in private.

295
00:12:50,300 --> 00:13:08,650
It's broken or something.

296
00:13:14,790 --> 00:13:16,650
Wow, Dad, if he weren't my uncle.

297
00:13:16,790 --> 00:13:18,890
I'd have to send you on vacation too.

298
00:13:19,030 --> 00:13:21,350
His attitude toward women is just awful.

299
00:13:21,950 --> 00:13:23,650
But you're too hard on him.

300
00:13:23,830 --> 00:13:24,790
He doesn't have it easy.

301
00:13:24,790 --> 00:13:26,430
Yeah, but neither do we.

302
00:13:26,430 --> 00:13:28,450
Why can't he just find a normal girlfriend?

303
00:13:28,450 --> 00:13:30,950
But it's not easy being Ozzak's girlfriend.

304
00:13:31,250 --> 00:13:36,550
Look, one went deaf at a Motorhead concert, she had to stand by the speaker to really enjoy it.

305
00:13:37,150 --> 00:13:40,650
And then there was that flight attendant who actually went to work at a brewery because of him.

306
00:13:41,150 --> 00:13:42,150
Now she's a lager.

307
00:13:42,650 --> 00:13:43,780
She ended up in the hospital?

308
00:13:44,150 --> 00:13:45,050
No, in the brewing vat.

309
00:13:45,250 --> 00:13:45,840
In Klasterec?

310
00:13:46,250 --> 00:13:49,050
In Krusovice, supposedly an accident.

311
00:13:49,350 --> 00:13:50,090
And what about you?

312
00:13:50,750 --> 00:13:52,450
Well, I haven't drunk beer since.

313
00:13:53,150 --> 00:13:54,850
No, I mean why haven't you found someone too?

314
00:13:54,850 --> 00:13:56,750
But I always attracted weird types.

315
00:13:56,750 --> 00:13:59,850
Look, once one forced me to sign my name ten times on a date.

316
00:13:59,900 --> 00:14:01,320
Wait, that's not so bad.

317
00:14:01,320 --> 00:14:05,980
Except she told me you can trade ten Pacovskys for one Schwarzenegger.

318
00:14:06,350 --> 00:14:07,650
That hurts.

319
00:14:08,250 --> 00:14:12,670
But there were some who wanted to stay with me, well, with us.

320
00:14:12,950 --> 00:14:15,510
But none of them passed Ozzak's entrance exam.

321
00:14:15,510 --> 00:14:16,050
And what was that?

322
00:14:16,170 --> 00:14:17,210
Chug a bottle of rum against the clock?

323
00:14:17,210 --> 00:14:20,450
No, prove that she loves you as much as he does.

324
00:14:23,150 --> 00:14:24,350
None of them passed.

325
00:14:36,550 --> 00:14:37,370
Can I come in?

326
00:14:37,750 --> 00:14:40,330
I just noticed it says "women entry forbidden" here.

327
00:14:40,550 --> 00:14:41,850
No, that's a typo.

328
00:14:42,450 --> 00:14:44,650
It should say "women entry commanded."

329
00:14:45,750 --> 00:14:46,730
Iva's here.

330
00:14:46,930 --> 00:14:49,470
We have to write an essay about spring and I don't know what to write.

331
00:14:49,630 --> 00:14:51,290
Why don't you ask Uncle Ozzak?

332
00:14:51,430 --> 00:14:52,710
He knows everything about spring.

333
00:14:56,050 --> 00:14:56,750
Come, sit down.

334
00:14:59,850 --> 00:15:00,650
Sit down?

335
00:15:01,150 --> 00:15:03,850
Nobody's ever said anything so nice to me.

336
00:15:06,450 --> 00:15:07,650
About spring, you say?

337
00:15:08,750 --> 00:15:15,350
If I had to write about spring, I'd write that it's the time of year when you feel completely different and feel things you don't usually feel.

338
00:15:16,050 --> 00:15:17,950
Suddenly the world is amazing.

339
00:15:18,050 --> 00:15:19,710
Like when you're wasted.

340
00:15:20,250 --> 00:15:23,250
But drunk on something else, something beautiful.

341
00:15:24,550 --> 00:15:27,250
Spring is like when they open the windows at the pub.

342
00:15:28,450 --> 00:15:31,980
Or they mop the bathrooms and bring those colorful little soaps.

343
00:15:31,980 --> 00:15:32,620
You know?

344
00:15:34,150 --> 00:15:36,160
Spring is like waking up in the morning after a party.

345
00:15:36,550 --> 00:15:39,050
Everyone's asleep, but the music's still playing.

346
00:15:40,850 --> 00:15:43,150
By the way, what music do you listen to, Sasa?

347
00:15:44,450 --> 00:15:45,750
Jarek Nohavica.

348
00:15:48,230 --> 00:15:48,870
And?

349
00:15:49,470 --> 00:15:50,110
And.

350
00:15:50,110 --> 00:15:50,650
And what?

351
00:15:51,850 --> 00:15:52,950
He also plays guitar, right?

352
00:15:53,050 --> 00:15:56,150
I keep babbling and I haven't offered you anything.

353
00:15:56,350 --> 00:15:57,260
Let me go to the kitchen.

354
00:15:57,260 --> 00:15:58,100
What do you want?

355
00:15:58,100 --> 00:16:06,550
For you to stay here with me, I can do something for you too.

356
00:16:08,750 --> 00:16:19,050
Well, can you tell me how I can, you know, do that...

357
00:16:24,150 --> 00:16:24,850
Click?

358
00:16:25,550 --> 00:16:27,850
Like on a computer?

359
00:16:29,750 --> 00:16:30,250
Yeah, with the mouse.

360
00:16:33,150 --> 00:16:33,980
The mouse?

361
00:16:35,250 --> 00:16:37,850
Obviously.

362
00:16:41,150 --> 00:16:41,650
Sasa, go home!

363
00:16:43,150 --> 00:16:45,250
This is a job for an experienced woman.

364
00:17:06,050 --> 00:17:06,550
What's going on?

365
00:17:08,050 --> 00:17:09,330
Tired of the Three Little Pigs?

366
00:17:11,450 --> 00:17:12,650
Are you in some cult?

367
00:17:13,050 --> 00:17:14,760
If so, I don't want a subscription.

368
00:17:15,250 --> 00:17:17,050
Mom, I have to tell you something.

369
00:17:17,750 --> 00:17:19,620
I'm in love.

370
00:17:20,150 --> 00:17:21,750
No way.

371
00:17:22,350 --> 00:17:25,650
And I bet five kilos it wouldn't happen until college.

372
00:17:26,150 --> 00:17:27,780
I'll take it out of your allowance.

373
00:17:27,780 --> 00:17:29,280
He's amazing, really.

374
00:17:29,700 --> 00:17:31,100
He actually cares about me.

375
00:17:31,850 --> 00:17:32,950
So he's a weirdo.

376
00:17:33,150 --> 00:17:34,250
That was to be expected.

377
00:17:35,350 --> 00:17:36,520
Well, that's nice.

378
00:17:36,850 --> 00:17:38,020
Try to enjoy it.

379
00:17:38,020 --> 00:17:38,960
Let it flow.

380
00:17:39,500 --> 00:17:40,580
It's not Lexa, right?

381
00:17:43,850 --> 00:17:44,750
Someone from school?

382
00:17:45,590 --> 00:17:46,510
So he's older?

383
00:17:47,950 --> 00:17:49,650
Great, experienced.

384
00:17:49,950 --> 00:17:51,150
He doesn't drink, by any chance?

385
00:17:51,650 --> 00:17:55,550
Great, he'll go to the pub in the evening and you'll have some peace.

386
00:17:56,050 --> 00:17:57,050
Is he clean?

387
00:17:58,330 --> 00:17:59,790
Excellent, you won't have to do his laundry.

388
00:18:00,270 --> 00:18:02,290
Girl, you've got good taste, just like me.

389
00:18:02,570 --> 00:18:03,790
And then you'll tell me who this boy is.

390
00:18:04,250 --> 00:18:04,670
You know him.

391
00:18:05,550 --> 00:18:07,650
It's Mr. Ozzak.

392
00:18:09,820 --> 00:18:10,300
Right.

393
00:18:12,050 --> 00:18:13,280
You know what, Sasenka?

394
00:18:13,550 --> 00:18:14,020
Come with me.

395
00:18:14,020 --> 00:18:15,780
Come with me to the back, I'll show you something.

396
00:18:15,900 --> 00:18:16,020
Come on.

397
00:18:28,750 --> 00:18:30,050
One day you'll thank me.

398
00:18:31,050 --> 00:18:31,830
Hey, Horvat.

399
00:18:32,090 --> 00:18:32,670
You got it?

400
00:18:40,950 --> 00:18:42,320
How much do you want for them?

401
00:18:42,320 --> 00:18:43,180
Two hundred.

402
00:18:43,520 --> 00:18:44,200
Per one?

403
00:18:45,150 --> 00:18:48,550
I'm a fool, two hundred per kilo.

404
00:18:55,050 --> 00:18:56,230
This one's the lightest, I'll take it.

405
00:18:56,550 --> 00:18:59,850
If you want, I've also got a fridge and a dishwasher on the cart.

406
00:19:00,250 --> 00:19:01,410
How much for the fridge?

407
00:19:01,650 --> 00:19:04,350
I can't open that fridge right now.

408
00:19:05,750 --> 00:19:07,350
It was stronger than me.

409
00:19:07,350 --> 00:19:10,770
Marcelka, you don't realize what could've happened.

410
00:19:10,790 --> 00:19:12,270
We got there just in time.

411
00:19:12,430 --> 00:19:14,090
He must have slipped something in my drink.

412
00:19:14,230 --> 00:19:14,990
And you were drinking?

413
00:19:15,770 --> 00:19:16,570
That's the thing, nothing.

414
00:19:19,050 --> 00:19:22,850
And he was so sweet and attentive that I almost felt like hugging him.

415
00:19:23,050 --> 00:19:26,350
In the morning you'd wake up and you know who'd be lying next to you?

416
00:19:26,570 --> 00:19:27,090
Him.

417
00:19:27,690 --> 00:19:29,390
Nobody would be lying next to you.

418
00:19:29,390 --> 00:19:33,450
Ozzak would've been at the pub ages ago and when he'd see you, he'd call you bimbo again.

419
00:19:33,750 --> 00:19:34,950
That scoundrel.

420
00:19:36,650 --> 00:19:37,350
What about Ozzak?

421
00:19:38,450 --> 00:19:40,750
I showed him where the mouse is on the computer and he looked happy.

422
00:19:42,150 --> 00:19:44,550
Gather yourselves, we'll figure something out.

423
00:19:44,970 --> 00:19:47,210
Tomas, now I really need that vacation.

424
00:19:48,250 --> 00:19:49,350
But what about Sasa?

425
00:19:50,310 --> 00:19:50,690
Sasa?

426
00:19:51,750 --> 00:19:52,130
Sasa?

427
00:19:53,050 --> 00:19:55,450
Mom said you don't need to worry about her.

428
00:19:56,090 --> 00:19:56,470
Weird.

429
00:19:56,850 --> 00:19:58,350
Who'd worry about her?

430
00:20:00,240 --> 00:20:02,460
Well, I really must be going, Mr. Pacovsky.

431
00:20:02,460 --> 00:20:06,350
I'll stop by to see my husband on the way, in case he's got it too.

432
00:20:06,640 --> 00:20:07,020
Spring.

433
00:20:11,780 --> 00:20:12,760
Impressed, huh?

434
00:20:13,280 --> 00:20:15,280
Now I've got Dana with me all the time.

435
00:20:15,460 --> 00:20:17,700
I need to check right away if she wrote me something.

436
00:20:19,510 --> 00:20:20,070
Nothing.

437
00:20:20,990 --> 00:20:21,370
Hey.

438
00:20:22,550 --> 00:20:23,680
Mr. Ozzak created an account on iwantawoman.

439
00:20:23,680 --> 00:20:24,700
cz.

440
00:20:25,050 --> 00:20:25,860
An account?

441
00:20:26,450 --> 00:20:27,240
What does that mean?

442
00:20:27,650 --> 00:20:30,340
It means he can arrange a date through the internet.

443
00:20:30,750 --> 00:20:32,700
Has he arranged any yet?

444
00:20:33,250 --> 00:20:33,740
I don't know.

445
00:20:34,250 --> 00:20:38,120
We'd need to know his password, which isn't easy to guess.

446
00:20:38,550 --> 00:20:39,450
Try Ozzak.

447
00:20:42,310 --> 00:20:42,950
We're in.

448
00:20:43,550 --> 00:20:45,250
Wow, you're a genius.

449
00:20:45,850 --> 00:20:48,650
I still had "beer" and "metal" in reserve.

450
00:20:49,450 --> 00:20:51,030
But what does that red number mean?

451
00:20:51,350 --> 00:20:54,080
It means Mr. Ozzak is a hit on the internet.

452
00:20:54,080 --> 00:20:55,260
Hundreds and hundreds of offers.

453
00:20:56,050 --> 00:20:57,740
Has he replied to any?

454
00:20:57,740 --> 00:20:58,140
Yeah.

455
00:20:59,050 --> 00:21:00,950
He even set up a date.

456
00:21:02,350 --> 00:21:05,950
My God, who's going to come after us this time? Who is this woman?

457
00:21:06,150 --> 00:21:08,110
Someone from the "serious offers only" section.

458
00:21:08,450 --> 00:21:10,130
Damn, she looks pretty dangerous.

459
00:21:10,850 --> 00:21:13,130
Her profile says "a kitty who likes to scratch."

460
00:21:13,130 --> 00:21:14,590
So Prkanova.

461
00:21:14,590 --> 00:21:17,050
No, Lada Kacanova.

462
00:21:17,250 --> 00:21:18,550
Kacanova the engineer?

463
00:21:19,050 --> 00:21:21,730
The one who handles commercial spaces at City Hall?

464
00:21:22,750 --> 00:21:24,350
She writes here, during the day I'm bored at the office.

465
00:21:24,420 --> 00:21:26,220
But at night my true self awakens.

466
00:21:26,660 --> 00:21:27,580
It's her.

467
00:21:28,250 --> 00:21:29,610
We'll lose the store.

468
00:21:29,610 --> 00:21:31,470
In an hour they have a date at Hotel Kopule.

469
00:21:31,470 --> 00:21:36,350
Hold Ozzak, I'll go after her, I'll try to explain it to her somehow.

470
00:21:38,050 --> 00:21:40,670
You could've just written to Ozzak that the date's cancelled.

471
00:21:40,950 --> 00:21:43,550
But you'd need to know her password.

472
00:21:46,350 --> 00:21:47,090
You mean Lada?

473
00:21:47,570 --> 00:21:48,090
Great.

474
00:21:49,350 --> 00:21:50,950
But you'd never guess my password.

475
00:21:59,180 --> 00:22:00,400
Only on the second try.

476
00:22:00,400 --> 00:22:05,050
I thought you knew Lexa is spelled with an X. Come on.

477
00:22:06,890 --> 00:22:07,710
Diana wrote you.

478
00:22:08,110 --> 00:22:08,650
Oh, show me.

479
00:22:09,150 --> 00:22:10,050
Is she on her way here?

480
00:22:10,650 --> 00:22:13,250
I can't take it anymore, we have to meet.

481
00:22:14,400 --> 00:22:15,180
What is it?

482
00:22:15,650 --> 00:22:16,850
Aren't you happy?

483
00:22:17,250 --> 00:22:19,260
I thought you couldn't wait to touch it.

484
00:22:19,650 --> 00:22:20,650
The bald head.

485
00:22:34,350 --> 00:22:35,850
Why aren't you going home, Lexa?

486
00:22:37,250 --> 00:22:39,150
I don't want to leave you here waiting alone.

487
00:22:39,650 --> 00:22:41,250
But I'm not waiting for anyone.

488
00:22:41,450 --> 00:22:44,850
Uncle wrote that it can be waited out and Dad should be home any minute.

489
00:22:45,650 --> 00:22:48,850
Why aren't you getting ready for your internet girlfriend?

490
00:22:49,850 --> 00:22:54,250
You know, the thing with Dana might actually be a bit different.

491
00:22:54,650 --> 00:22:56,450
What happened, what happened?

492
00:22:57,150 --> 00:23:00,150
She wrote you that her middle name is Helmut.

493
00:23:05,150 --> 00:23:08,650
We'll keep the store, don't ask me anything.

494
00:23:16,750 --> 00:23:19,160
No, no, no, don't ask me anything.

495
00:23:24,250 --> 00:23:25,190
I'm here.

496
00:23:25,190 --> 00:23:26,390
Thank God, Bejk.

497
00:23:27,710 --> 00:23:28,270
Uncle!

498
00:23:30,850 --> 00:23:32,550
Don't ask me anything, kiddo.

499
00:23:35,150 --> 00:23:40,850
So it looks like I can finally take down the sign that says women forbidden.

500
00:23:45,050 --> 00:23:46,580
Oh, Lexa.

501
00:23:46,850 --> 00:23:48,250
Hey, Uncle, what's up?

502
00:23:48,450 --> 00:23:51,450
Give me that laptop, quick.

503
00:23:53,050 --> 00:23:55,250
Don't ask me anything.

504
00:23:59,350 --> 00:24:01,320
You're lucky, Horvat.

505
00:24:01,550 --> 00:24:06,400
Now go get that fridge and maybe you'll get off with probation.

506
00:24:06,400 --> 00:24:06,960
See ya.

507
00:24:14,750 --> 00:24:16,670
Hey, Lexa, hi.

508
00:24:17,050 --> 00:24:22,150
But I'm not Lexa, Lexa is over there.

509
00:24:23,990 --> 00:24:24,710
What?

510
00:24:25,950 --> 00:24:26,350
So you're not Danuska?

511
00:24:26,350 --> 00:24:31,350
But I'm exactly as sensitive as you know me.

512
00:24:34,250 --> 00:24:37,850
My friends told me the internet is full of creeps.

513
00:24:38,840 --> 00:24:39,560
Pig.

514
00:24:44,010 --> 00:24:45,850
Don't ask me anything.

515
00:24:55,450 --> 00:24:56,750
You can't fight nature.

516
00:25:24,850 --> 00:25:26,270
I resisted.

